CLI Solution
You can use the following Azure CLI command to create the VM xfusion-vm with the specified configurations:
az vm create \
  --resource-group <your-resource-group> \
  --name xfusion-vm \
  --image Ubuntu2204 \
  --size Standard_B2s \
  --admin-username azureuser \
  --generate-ssh-keys \
  --storage-sku Standard_LRS \
  --os-disk-size-gb 30 \
  --no-wait

Verifying the VM is Running
Once the VM creation is initiated, you can check the status of the VM using the following command:

az vm get-instance-view --resource-group <your-resource-group> --name xfusion-vm --query "instanceView.statuses[1].displayStatus"

SSH into the VM
After the VM has been created, you can connect to it via SSH using the following command (make sure you have the SSH private key associated with the generated keys):
ssh azureuser@<public-ip-address>
